<tt>Sun Nov  2  0:17:45 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Pee Pee:<br><br>
Had a Chopper Jock buddy fly in from Florida.. drove up from Dallas this afternoon.  He did three tours in RVN... loaded up with bells, whistles, medals (big boys) and a lot of shiney stuff as Cookie puts it.  Wife fixed him a big supper..he an I talked about Alaska, Saudi Arabia, Africa, South America, Rocky Mountains etc. etc etc. until we finaly got around to Viet Nam.<br><br>
He feels guilty because he took an R&amp;R while his unit got the crap kicked out of them.  Had some buddies crash...He hovered close to the burning wreckage to blow the flames away from the crew...made the fire hotter and spare .45 cal rounds began to cook off in the pilot's pistol gear.  He rescued them all.  So overjoyed that these close friends had survived..he landed and went immediately to the hospital...grabbed one of the pilot's hands and began to squeeze it and shake it vigoriously...not knowing that the man's hand was broken.  Tragic humor!<br>
Doesn't remember the hundreds of grunts that he saved.. only remembers the ones who didn't make it.<br>
Has a ton of medals for heroism and valor but is embarrassed that he was never wounded.<br>
I blurt out all kinds of sincere adulation..but it falls on deaf ears.  I want to grab him by the collar and shake him and scream in his face how much I love and respect him..but the dullness in his eyes tells me that it would do no good. So, I just stand next to him feeling him love me but denying me the priviledge of loving him.<br>
Of all the sadness I know..this is the worst form.<br>
One of my Brothers of Choice recently posted that we had made him feel better about himself for his service in RVN.  I must admit that &quot;good&quot; tears came to my eyes.<br>
I salute all of you and thank you for &quot;Being There!&quot;<br><br>
Welcome Home<br><br>
P.S.  PP...Got your 3 bucks, thanks.  Gort..good to have you posting.
